Do you have any extra masks or know of anyone still making masks?

We do not plan to require students to wear masks, but rather we are planning for an extensive lists of possible needs for the future. Thank you in advance üôÇ

April 29, 2020
To our students, families, and community members:

We are hopeful that social distancing restrictions will be easing as the summer progresses, and we will all be able to get back to some sense of normal. Therefore, we would like our students and families to keep the following dates open on your calendars.

Option 1:
High School Awards Night ‚Äì Wednesday, June 24 6:00 in the High School Commons
Grand March / Prom ‚Äì Friday, June 26 8:00 ‚Äì 11:30pm in the High School Commons
Graduation ‚Äì Sunday, June 28 2:00 in the High School Gold Gym.

If restrictions are not lifted in time, we will go to Option 2
High School Awards Night ‚Äì Wednesday, August 5 - 6:00 in the High School Commons
Grand March / Prom ‚Äì Friday, August 7 - 8:00 ‚Äì 11:30pm in the High School Commons
Graduation ‚Äì Sunday, August 9 2:00 in the High School Gold Gym.

Thank you for your patience as we have tried to schedule alternative dates.

post_text: In these uncertain times we are especially thankful for our small communities that make us Midland Strong! Whenever there is a need; we call friends and neighbors, pull resources together, and make things happen! You helped organize a district wide parade to boost student and teacher morale. Local libraries provided activities/materials for students, and the fire departments escorted the Easter Bunny through towns today! Hearts and bears on windows remind us to stay positive, be kind to others and support essential workers! We appreciate your support!! #midlandstrong

post_text:
During this time of so many unknowns, please know there are people to help us!

Dear Midland Families, These images show exercises for self- regulation and quick tips for de-escalation techniques you could utilize with your kiddos. The exercise image shows a quick 7 minute workout that your kiddos could do in the home (or outside). These exercises have descriptions explaining how to use them. This is used to help kids stay active and keep moving. The other image shows de-escalation techniques if you have a kiddo having a difficult time regulating, getting frustrated easily, expressing anxiety/worry or maybe just need to reset during this time. There is also a description to help guide you and your kiddo in use.

Aspen Felton, MA, tLMHC.
Therapist
Anamosa Office/ School Based Therapist Midland Elementary School
209 W. Main St.
Anamosa, IA 52205
Cell:563-542-8370
Office: 319-313-5510
E-mail: a.felton@life-connections.org
www.life-connections.org
Facebook: www.facebook.com/lifeconnections4u

Midland Middle / High School
May 9, 2019 at 9:07 PM ¬∑

Midland needs substitute teachers for the 2019-2020 School year!

Who can earn the Substitute Authorization License?
Anyone who meets the following criteria can receive a Substitute Authorization license:

Has earn a four year college degree and
is at least 21 years old; and
Passes the Iowa Division of Criminal Investigation and National Criminal History background checks; and
Completes a Substitute Authorization course.

How to Earn the Substitute Authorization License

Take the Substitute Authorization course from an AEA.
You may take the course from any AEA:
To Register, create an account at: https://goo.gl/vHzGYw
cost: $140
format: 18 hours of class time, 2+ hours of online work
Send your application, documentation, and fees to the BOEE:
Finger print cards and signed FBI background check form (provided at the first class)
transcript from four-year college degree
transcript from the AEA showing successful complete of the Substitute Authorization course
$85 application fee plus $75 background check fee; total of $160

post_text:
Dear Midland Community,

I wanted to inform our Midland families about Mr. Becker, one of our 5th grade teachers . Nathan was in a tree cutting accident on Sunday. He was airlifted to St. Luke‚Äôs and had surgery to remove a blood clot on the outside of his brain. He also had some fractures in his skull and a vertebra. He is in intensive care and is still sedated.

Many people have reached out to the school to help. We will be posting more specific information to help as we get things set up. If you want to post a message for Mr. Becker on here or send a card, please drop it off at the school and we will give it to the family. I know Mrs Becker is reading him the comments and appreciates your support.

Your outpouring of love and support for the Becker family has been overwhelming. This is what makes Midland the greatest community.

Thank you,
Mrs Ruley
